<answer>Because $z^7 - 1 = (z - 1) \prod_{1 \leq k \leq 6} (z - z_k),$ where $z_k$ is the $k^{th}$ roots of unity of $z^7 - 1,$ we find that the roots of $z^7 + z^6 + \ldots + z + 1 = 0$ are precisely the roots of $z^7 - 1 = 0$ excluding $z = 1.$ Our polygon $P$ is just the unit circle $|z| = 1$ with a triangle removed (either way) whose vertices are $1, z_2,$ and $z_3$. Let us count the signed area of the triangle: $z_2 = \cos (\frac{2\pi}{7}) + i \sin (\frac{2\pi}{7}),$ $z_3 = \cos (\frac{3\pi}{7}) + i \sin (\frac{3\pi}{7}),$
\begin{align*}
A & = \frac{1}{2} z_2 \overline{ z_3} - \frac{1}{2} z_3 \overline{ z_2} \\
& = \frac{1}{2} \left( \cos (\frac{2}{7} \pi ) \cos (\frac{3}{7} \pi ) + \sin (\frac{2}{7} \pi ) \sin (\frac{3}{7} \pi ) - \sin (\frac{2}{7} \pi ) \cos (\frac{3}{7} \pi ) - \sin (\frac{2}{7} \pi ) \cos (\frac{3}{7} \pi ) \right) \\
& = \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{1}{2} \left( \cos (\frac{- \pi}{7} \pi ) - \cos (\frac{1}{7} \pi ) \right) \\
& = \frac{1}{4} \left( \frac{1}{2} \right) = \frac{1}{8}
\end{align*}
